crates/ctx-verify/src is the ctx-verify crate itself: a broker that shells out to cargo/clippy/rustdoc/scripts, normalizes their output into diagnostics, and emits one capped, deterministic JSON verification report for CI and ctx-run to parse.

The layering is strict and runs main.rs → cli.rs → checks.rs → (parse.rs + runner.rs) → model.rs. runner.rs is the only file that spawns processes (`Runner` trait, `ProcRunner`); checks.rs is written purely against that trait so tests inject fakes instead of shelling out. checks.rs owns the fixed `SPECS` list (fmt, clippy, doc, test, rationale, workspace_lints, no_allow) and, for each, picks a parser from parse.rs to turn raw stdout into `Diagnostic`s, then hands results to model.rs's `CheckReport::build`/`Report::new` to compute status and truncation. cli.rs and main.rs are pure argv/IO wiring — no check logic lives there.

Shared coupling: `Diagnostic`'s field shape (file, line, col, lint, message) is produced in parse.rs and consumed by model.rs and cli.rs's terse renderer — a field change ripples through all three. Error taxonomy is centralized in error.rs's `CheckError` and referenced by runner.rs (spawn failures), checks.rs (ToolMissing vs errored vs synthesized-failure distinction), and cli.rs (Encode/Write mapping). The JSON shape from model.rs is the wire contract other tools (ctx-run, CI) parse — described as schema-compatible with a broader "spec's audit report" family, so model.rs changes need to stay in sync with whatever else reads that family, not just this crate.

Subtree invariants: a check that fails to spawn (other than missing tool) always becomes `errored`, never a silent `fail`; a failing check with no parsed diagnostics always gets exactly one synthesized diagnostic (checks.rs `failure_hint`); diagnostics per check are capped at `max` with excess recorded in `truncated`, never silently dropped; top-level `Status` prioritizes Errored > Fail > Pass, ignoring Skipped; and `fmt` is the only mutating check, must stay first in SPECS.

No intent.md is present for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.